#OTD in NE History: In 1943, the North Platte Daily Bulletin noted the inspiring generosity of Gene Slattery, an 11-year-old from Big Springs who donated $36.50 to the North Platte Canteen after selling his own chickens and clothing at auction.

Beginning at age 9, Gene began selling everything he could find: toys, scrap metal, animals, even the shirt off his back to support the Canteen effort. By the end of WWII, he had raised more than $2,000.

The paper also shared a letter thanking Canteen volunteers from deployed Army serviceman Ralph Powers who, as a former Union Pacific employee from North Platte, had “helped haul of lot of fellows through there.”

Powers said, “I want the people of North Platte to know that we are doing our best over here and with your help will keep our grass nice and green to come back to, regardless of the price. Keep up the good work. People like you are which makes home worth coming back to.”

@SenatorFischer and I sponsor legislation to award the Congressional Gold Medal to Canteen volunteers who served millions of American troops during WWII.

#OTD in NE History:  In 1943, on the front page of the Cozad Local, the community’s men announced they were prepared with sufficient funds to operate a “Cozad Day” at the #NorthPlatteCanteen on #FathersDay. Although, they welcomed donations of homemade birthday cakes—a “great hit” with servicemembers.

The same day, a letter appeared in the North Platte Daily Telegraph from an American soldier in the South Pacific. Identified only as a native of Omaha, the soldier had not visited the canteen but “felt he had to make a comment” after finding a feature on it titled “A Little Town with a Big Heart” in Liberty magazine.

Noting his pride in his home state, he wrote, “It makes one feel that the home front is willing to go to the limit to make life as pleasant as possible. There will be a lot of us that won’t come back, but folks like you make it truer than ever, ‘It Is Worth Fighting For.”

He closed by saying, “When the lights come, and the ships sail home in peace, I will stop for a piece of that delicious looking home-made cake.”

@SenatorFischer and I sponsor legislation to award the Congressional Gold Medal to canteen volunteers who went to the limit as they served nearly 7 million soldiers during WWII.

#OTD in NE History: In 1943, the Syracuse Journal-Democrat recorded a late spring heat wave and storms combined to result in stifling humidity. The patriotic wartime attitude of Nebraskans was captured in a quote from a local Syracusean, “Why complain? Think of the boys in Africa!”

The following day, a letter from “somewhere in Africa” appeared in the North Platte Daily Telegraph, sent by American Captain Adolphe J. Dickman who lauded the hospitality of “The charming ladies of the North Platte Canteen.”

In the letter he recalled the “far away dream” of coming through North Platte the day after Christmas and receiving “hot coffee, sandwiches, coffee again, chewing gum and a swell Christmas present.”

Capt. Dickman was born in Belgium and immigrated to the U.S. following decorated service in the First World War. He was a professor of language at Baylor University, Iowa, and Wyoming before serving as a liaison officer for French and American forces during the North African campaign.

In gratitude to the North Platte Canteen, he wrote, “attentions like those you gave are not forgotten…Keep the home fires burning and remember the boys ‘somewhere all over the world.’”

@SenatorFischer and I sponsor legislation to award the Congressional Gold Medal to Canteen volunteers who kept the home fires burning as they served nearly 7 million soldiers during WWII.

#OTD in NE History: In 1943, the North Platte Daily Telegraph printed this moving letter written by a soldier from Hawaii, who praised the hospitality and “wide awake and hustling spirit” of the North Platte Canteen as “good morale builders.”

Private Larry T. Mizumoto passed through Nebraska on his way to Mississippi’s Camp Shelby and wrote of his motivation to volunteer for a combat team composed of Japanese Americans, “our hearts are all for America. We have been through Pearl Harbor…Some of us lost our good friends and even brothers and sisters and dear Mom and Dad on that fateful day…and we are here to see that Tojo and his stooges are put just where they belong.”

He said of willingness to do his patriotic duty, “We realize that a lot of us won’t be coming home when it’s over, over there. But as long as there are such people like you folks in this country, America, land of liberty and justice, we are more than willing to die for you.” Sadly, Private Mizumoto lost his life two months before the surrender of Japan on July 8, 1945, in what is recorded as a non-combat death. His courage, sacrifice, and stirring message are not forgotten.

Private Franco wrote their outstanding hospitality was inspiring for his will to serve his country saying, "Believe me, a town like McCook, Neb., is worth fighting for."  

Sharing the remarks of fellow soldiers from New York City and elsewhere who were so impacted by the kindness they were shown, Franco said, “You see, deep inside America, hidden out in the plains and hills, are the folks who make up America. Lots of these fellows never knew that."  

My bill with @SenatorFischer would award the Congressional Gold Medal to volunteers from across Nebraska who supported World War II canteen efforts.

Today with @RepGaramendi I introduced the Medicare IVIG Access Enhancement Act to expand access to home infusion treatments for Medicare beneficiaries with certain conditions requiring intravenous immunoglobulin (IVIG) infusion treatments. Currently, these Americans are at risk because their access to treatment depends on access to an infusion facility.

This bipartisan bill would make vital in-home IVIG treatments accessible and improve health outcomes for patients living with Chronic Inflammatory Demyelinating Polyneuropathy (CIDP) and Multifocal Motor Neuropathy (MMN).

In a statement @gbscidp said the organization “wholeheartedly supports this critical piece of legislation that will ensure that patients will be able to access a life-sustaining treatment in their own homes, fixing a longstanding gap in coverage and accessibility for patients with CIDP and MMN.”
